.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8AD842ABFFAD0806FF5D08F6FB81682F" lastPageId="7" pageId="6" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C27D1120FFAD0807FF5D08F6FC376EB3" blockId="6.[151,1437,764,2016]" pageId="6">
<emphasis id="F0B6CD32FFAD0807FF5D08F6FE996ED7" bold="true" box="[199,334,1953,1979]" pageId="6">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is composed of the Latin adjective“ 
<emphasis id="F0B6CD32FFAD0807FC4A08F6FBED6ED7" box="[976,1082,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="6">violaceus</emphasis>
ˮ (violet) and substantive “ 
<emphasis id="F0B6CD32FFAD0807FAF708F6FF136EB3" italics="true" pageId="6">dorsum</emphasis>
ˮ (dorsal part of he body) to stress the violet colouration of the species.
</paragraph>
